I'm currently using the bash shell on arch. Thinking of using fish. Can I run them in parallel? discuss with me

Gemini said
Making the jump from Bash to Fish is like moving from a reliable old pickup truck to a sleek electric sports car. It’s faster and much prettier out of the box, but the engine works a bit differently under the hood.

The short answer is yes, absolutely. You can run them "in parallel" in several ways without breaking your system.

1. How to Run Them Side-by-Side
You don't have to commit to Fish immediately. Here are the three best ways to test the waters:

The "Guest" Method: Simply type fish in your current Bash terminal. This starts a Fish shell as a child process. When you're done, type exit to go back to Bash.

The Terminal Emulator Method: Most terminal emulators (like Alacritty, Kitty, or Konsole) allow you to set a custom command for new tabs. You can have one tab running Bash and another running Fish simultaneously.

The "Login vs. Interactive" Split: Keep Bash as your system default shell (so scripts don't break) but set your terminal emulator to open Fish by default. This is the safest way to "use" Fish daily while keeping your system environment standard.

2. The "Gotcha": POSIX Compliance
This is the most important thing to understand when running both. Bash is POSIX-compliant; Fish is not.

Feature	Bash Syntax	Fish Syntax
Setting Variables	export FOO=bar	set -x FOO bar
Command Substitution	VAR=$(ls)	set VAR (ls)
Combining Commands	cmd1 && cmd2	cmd1; and cmd2 (or && in newer versions)
Loops	for i in {1..5}; do ... done	for i in (seq 5); ... end
Pro Tip: Do not change your default user shell using chsh -s /usr/bin/fish immediately. Some system scripts on Arch expect a POSIX-compliant shell. While /bin/sh usually points to Bash or Dash, keeping your user shell as Bash and just launching Fish in your terminal avoids weird edge-case bugs.

3. Dealing with your .bashrc
Your .bashrc aliases and functions will not work in Fish. You will need to migrate them to ~/.config/fish/config.fish.

However, there is a handy tool called "Bass" (available in the AUR) that allows you to run Bash commands/scripts from within Fish. This is a lifesaver if you have a complex script you aren't ready to rewrite yet.

4. Why Fish on Arch is Great
Since you're on Arch, you'll appreciate the interactive suggestions and tab completion. Fish looks at your history and your files to guess what you’re typing in real-time. On Arch, Fish’s completions for pacman are incredibly robust—it can often suggest specific package names before you’ve typed more than two letters.

My recommendation? Install Fish with sudo pacman -S fish, open your terminal, type fish, and play around.

