Gemini said
When you run a shell inside tmux, environment variables (like $PATH, $EDITOR, or your API keys) can get "stuck" or behave differently depending on how the session was started.

Since you are considering running Bash and Fish in parallel, you need to be aware of how they handle these variables, especially because their syntax for setting them is totally different.

1. The Syntax Divide
This is the biggest hurdle when jumping between the two. If you copy a "How-to" guide for a new tool, it will almost always give you the Bash version.

Feature	Bash (.bashrc)	Fish (config.fish)
Standard Var	FOO=bar	set FOO bar
Export (Env Var)	export FOO=bar	set -x FOO bar
Appending to PATH	export PATH="$HOME/bin:$PATH"	fish_add_path ~/bin
The Risk: If you set a variable in Bash and then launch Fish inside that Bash shell, Fish will inherit it. But if you change it in Fish, it won't "trickle back" to the parent Bash shell.

2. The tmux "Zombie" Variable Problem
tmux acts as a middleman. When you start a tmux server, it captures the environment variables of the shell that spawned it.

The Scenario: You update your $PATH in your ~/.bashrc.

The Problem: You go into an existing tmux pane and run source ~/.bashrc. The shell is updated, but the tmux session itself still holds the old version of the variable.

The Result: If you open a new window or pane (whether it's Fish or Bash), it might inherit the old variable from the tmux server instead of your updated config.

Tip: In tmux, you can run tmux show-environment to see what variables the "server" is currently holding hostage.

3. Universal Variables (The Fish Superpower)
Fish has a unique feature called Universal Variables (set -U).
If you run set -U MY_THEME "dracula" in one Fish pane, every other Fish shell on your system (current and future) instantly knows that variable. You don't even have to add it to a config file.

Bash has nothing like this. If you use Universal Variables in Fish, remember that your Bash panes will be completely oblivious to them.

4. How to Handle Both Safely
If you're going to use both, here is the best "Arch/Ghostty/Tmux" strategy:

Keep Global Stuff in .pam_environment or /etc/environment: Put things that both shells need (like EDITOR=nvim or BROWSER=firefox) here. This way, they are set at login before any shell even starts.

Use fish_add_path: Instead of manually hacking the $PATH variable in Fish (which is a mess of colons in Bash but a "list" in Fish), just use the command fish_add_path /your/path. It’s smart enough to not add duplicates.

The "Bass" Plugin: Since you're on Arch, you can install bash-completion and the Fish plugin Bass. Bass lets you run Bash scripts (like those annoying env.sh scripts some programs give you) and injects the resulting variables directly into your Fish session.

